{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893786/1930111901/0331.xml":{"full_text":"\u00aehe Itammsuttk Herald\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter tn the Postoffice.\nBrownsville. Texas.\nTHE BROWNSVILLE BERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entiMed to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to It or\nnot otherwise credited In this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nBttbecrlption Rates\u2014Dally and Sunday (7 Issues)\nOne Year. *9.00\nSix Month:; *450\nThree Months *235\nOne Month .75\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDellas. Texas. 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City, Mo, 306 Coca-Cola Building.\nChicago, m., Association Building.\nNew York. 350 Madison Avenue.\nSt. Louis, 502 Star Building.\nLob Angeles. Cal., Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg.,\n848 8. Broadway.\nSan Francisco. Cal.. 318 Kohl Building.\nBrownsville Has:\n1. A population in 1930 of 22.050.\n2. A mean average temperature of *3.\n3. Bank deposits, $8,000,000.\n4. Four railroads, seven paved highways.\n5. International airport, five air lines.\n6. A $6,000,000 deep water port financed.\n7. The best climate, soil in the world.\nSeeking The Same Goal\nFriendship Is a strange sort of thing. It appears,\nsometime?, where you would least expect it, and\nflourishes in spots where you would suppose that it\ncould find nothing whatever to feed on.\nBo it is with the friendship between Clarence Dar\nrow and Dr. Clarence True Wilson. It was revealed\nat Houston recently that these two men. who are in\npublic bitter foes on almost any question one can call\nto mind, are in private extremely warm friends. The\nwet agnostic and the dry fundamentalist have de\nbated with each other a great deal and have traveled\ntogether a great deal; and somewhere they have\nfound a common ground, where mutual admiration\nand esteem can grow unchecked.\nDr. Wilson\u2019s discussion of the growth of this friend\nship is very much worth reading. It Increases, some\nhow. one's respect for both men He says;\n\u201cThe fact is, if anybody can be a Christian without\nknowing it, I think It would be Clarence Darrow, for\nif you make a list of the Christian qualities which\na Christian ought to have, such as living according to\nthe Golden R ile, loving everybody, taking up for the\nones who need it mo?t. standing against privilege\nand In favor of the unpriviliged. he lives what we\nteach as the best standards of life.\u201d\nThat, ooming from a devout churchman to a man\nwho mounts lecture platform* to denounce religion,\ncoming from a militant dry to one of the nation's\nmost outspoken wets, is a remarkable tribute, ll\npoints to something that is of considerable import\nance; namely, that men can travel toward the same\n*oal by the most diverse roads, and that they can\nmake the going smoother for themselves and others\nif they are broad enough to realize that there are. in\nthe old phrase, many paths to salvation.\nEach of these men has devoted his life to a battle\nfor the truth as he has seen it. Each one has fought\nlustily for the sake of a cause. Each of them has\nbeen, and is. what we call a visionary\u2014a man who\nhas caught a glimpse of the fair place that men might\nmake of this world if they only would, and who can\nnot rest until he has given all of his energy and all of\nhis strength to the expounding of his vision.\nOn the surface, they have been violently opposed.\nBut underneath? They are working toward the same\nend\u2014to make the world a more decent place, to re\nmove a bit of its sin and suffering and hopelessne?.-,\nto enable people to get more out of their lives in the\nshape of happiness and the fulfillment of high de\nsires.\nIf the rest of us\u2014followers of one or the other of\nthese two men. or perhaps occupants of the wide\nmiddle ground between them\u2014could only realize ai\nthey have realized that we are. after all, seeking a\ncommon goal, even though we can't agree on the be\u00abt\nmethod of getting there, wouldn't there be a good\ndeal less bitterness and misunderstanding in American\nlife todav? And wouldn't that be an excellent thing\nfor all of us?\nj The Once Over1\nL By H. L PHILLIPS\n1\nHELP THE POOR BOOTLEGGER\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Associated Newspapers.)\nThe bootlegging business Is in a depression. Never\nsince prohibition, according to reports, have the boot\nleggers had such a hard time making a dishonest\nliving.\n\nMany of them are in such dire straits that they\ndon\u2019t know where the wife's next diamond necklace\nis coming from.\n\nThey are having a difficult struggle to keep the i\nwolf from the labeling plant.\n\nUnless better times come very soon thousands of\nour best known bootleggers will have to give up their\nprivate yachts, get along with one limousine and sub\nlease their hunting estates.\n\nIn some cities the supply so far exceeds the de\nmand that they have stopped cutting the liquor with\nwater, industrial alcohol, piano polish and coloring\nextracts.\n\nDuring the prosperous era there was no industry\nthat boomed more than the liquor industry. The boys\ndidn\u2019t even have to send out salesmen. Orders pour\ned in over the telephone and all shipments were made\ncollect on delivery. The policy was never to give a\ncustomer an even break.\n\nThe only thing that flattened a consumer more\nthan the liquor itself was the schedule of prices. If\nhe could survive both he was a Grade A insurance\nrisk.\n\nI\nThe roar of the bootleggers' trucks was loud in the\nland and great was the prosperity of the poison ped\ndlers. Prices were subject to increase without notice\nand it was not considered cricket for a buyer to make\nany critical comment if he opened a bottle marked\n\u2018Rare Old Parr Rye\" and found it to contain raw\nturpentine.\n\nNow all is changed \u2018\u2018Buy Now\" would have been\na great slogan in the old saloon days but it is a dud\nas a business promoter in the alcohol industry\n\nSince the market break of a year ago the custom\ners have practically withdrawn in a body and con\nditions have reached a point where the bootleggers\nare almost ready to turn honest.\nI\nThey are even ready to sell stuff In the original\nbottle.\n\nSome of the largest bootleggers are economizing to\nsuch an extent that they have closed their art de\npartments and are using only one design of label.\nI\nThe boys are really in a bad way. They could get\na better break selling apples on street corners. If\nthe situation gets any worse you may see the unprece\ndented spectacle of bootleggers in bread lines.\n\nAnd if you do we hope the bread they get is syn\nthetic and incorrectly labeled.\nMarked Down To 35 Cents\nThe bargain book lay on the counter forlorn.\nIts battered face covered with dirt:\nTo a very rude bookworm It said with a sigh.\n\u201cI'm not angry but terribly hurt!\"\nAphasia.\nA kindergarten teacher came upon a little waif\nreaching into the bowl and squeezing a goldfish, and\nthen saying, ruefully. \u201cHe don\u2019t go no more.\"\nPossibly what the stock market needs is a theme\nsong replacing the old one known as T\u2019ve Got a Feel\ning I'm Falling.\"\nSuggestion for another business revival slogan:\nMoney makes the scare go!\"\nMovie Magazine\nPictures of some\nFamous stars.\nStories of their\nPas and Mas,\nGirls at whom the\nShieks all stare\nAnd a new star\u2019s\nUnderwear.\nL. C. Ovens.\nOur Boarding House By Ahem\nI xTos-r uwe.]||s/ weuL.AM egad, f\u00ae\ne wav Rf you see um\nA5-me MAXTORf'l AS I SAID\nSAVS Moui UM-M PAk/lD, ABOU\u201cT -THE\n\"TVfE PRfAicE A PAulPo/kl, I K/AJGJ S<AMP\n'T'EASIMgLV *y\\ MEA/kA 7IS y COLLECT? OAi|\nPETERS -fa ',lGh(^E55, 4/klP, cA\nVGU A5 \"NUBBV7i 15 A OMuIM/Mg) NE5 Po/UY\nctf ap f torge-t -tPa-t\n\u2014^^^qli -EM D\n-WOUl,COMFlDEM^AU>0^^^ ME SPS/kiT\nSIR -TPoR/kTfb/ki -m7 _r^ UJrTVl GEORGE\n-W/LL^E PRl/ki CE \\B\u00a3R*dARP SMAUl\niti_^RRV7 >^-X _ J~HAU!-PEAR\n4 OLD GEORGIE\nt: X\nijv/S peceptToaJ -toW\nSIR \u201cTWopu-rb/ki \\i\ni mo nu st*vK.t me. K- iq\n\nHeart jHunffry\nby c 'wo NtA Yewct /\u00abc\nBEGIN HERE TODAY\nCelia Mitchell. 17, leaves Balti\nmore. where she has lived with her\nseamstress mother, Margaret Rogers,\nto join her father, John Mitchell, in\nNew York. The parents are divorced\nand Mrs. Rogers is a widow follow\ning a second marriage\nBarney Shields, young newspaper\nphotographer, is in love with the\ngirl Mitchell asks Evelyn Parsons\nbeautiful widow, to introduce the\ndaughter to other young people. Mrs.\nParsons agrees, considering Celia\na rreans to win Mitchell's affections\nShe soon becomes jealous of the\ngirl and schemes to get rid of her\nby encouraging a romance between\nCflla and Tod Jordan, fascinating,\nbut of dubious reputation.\nMitchell has forbidden his daugh\nter to see Jordan. Shields comes\nto New York to work for a photo\ngraphic service and meets Celia.\nShe tells him she cares for Tod Jor\ndan but later realizes it is Barney\nwhom she loves.\nMrs. Parsons goes to Mitchell and\ntells him the girl has been meeting\nShields surreptitiously. Father and\ndaughter quarrel and Celia leaves\nfor Baltimore. Her mother Is not\nthere and all clews to Mrs Rogers*\nwhereabouts fail. Mitchell arrives\nHe and Celia become reconciled\nand return to New' York after he has\np omtsed to locate Mrs. Rogers.\nMearwhtle. Mrs. Parsons invites\nShields to dinner and tells him Cel\nia is to marry Jordan. Next day\nCelia and Lisi go to a matinee and\nencounter Jordan. All three are\ntogether when they meet Shields.\nCelia leaves the others to talk to\nShields. The interview ends with\nthe understanding that all is over\nbetween them That evening Mrs.\nParsons announces to Celia that\nMitchell has asked her to marry\nhim.\nNOW GO ON WITH THE STORY\nCH APTER LIII\n\u201cYou mean\u2014!\u201d Celia began and\nthen she stopped From the ex\npression of Evelyn Parsons' face\nthere was no doubt that what the\nwoman had said was true.\nMrs. Parsons laughed and the\nsound was strident \u201cI mean just\nj what I said.\" Evelyn continued\nl Your father has asked m^ to be his\nv ife- and I have accepted I must\nsay I'm disappointed. Celia. You\ndon't look \\ery pleased!\"\nThe girl was staring at her. For\na moment she said nothing. Then\nshe leaned forward eyeing Evelyn\nappealingly and the words burst\nforth:\nBut I thought\u2014I mean when\nmother comes back\u2014oh. Evelyn, it\nwouldn't be right! You wouldn't do\nsuch a thing! Mother loves him\nstill. I know she does.\"\nEvelyn Parsons' shoulders straigh\ntrned. \"So you disapprove!\" she\nsaid coldly. \u201cRcallj\u2019. my dear. I\ntlnnk it would have been more polite\nif you concealed your feelings. After\nall. your father and I are both\ngrown adults able to think for our\nselves. I had no idea you disliked\nme so much!\"\n\"Oh. it isn't that! Of course I\ndon't dislike you. Please don't think\nme ungrateful for ail you've done!\nBut don't you see what they both\nmean to me? Mother\u2014\u2019\u2019\n\u201cThere is no nred for voti to sav\nany more. And I shall tell you\nfrankly that if your mother were\nin this very room tonight begging\nme to give him up It would not alter\nmv plans in the sliehtes*.. Do you\nthink I\u2019d let your fathpr make a\nfool of himself over that woman a\nsecond time? Do vou think I have\nno feelings? No rights? Why do you\ni\"\"'\" i.\nI cling to this ridiculous notion that\nyour lather and mother, separated\nwhen you were a child, would be any\nhappier together now? I tell you\nit's preposterous. They made one\nmistake, discovered it and parted.\nDo you think you could possibly\nbring them together again? No!\nMis. Parsons' eyes flashed. Anger\nhad gotten the better of her usual\nsuavity. The exhibition of temper\nheld Celia spellbound.\n\"John and I love each other.\"\nEvelyn went on. \"It will be useless\n'or you to attempt to interfen*\nJohn's been devoted to me for years\nReally. Celia. I should think you'd\n'consider his happiness even if you\n\u25a0dislike me!\u201d\n\"You mustn\u2019t say that. Evelyn. 1\ndo like you. It's just that it's such\na surprise. I was startled.\u201d\n\nBut why should you be surprised?\nSurely you must have known he\nwas fond of me. Why. I\u2019ve been\nputting him off for months! I had\nto respect Dwight's memory but it\u2019s\na year since he left me\u2014or practi\ncally a year John and Dwight were\nsuch friends. That\u2019s one reason I\nfeel the hand of fate is guiding me\nOf course, it will be some time be\nfore the engagement can be an\nnounced You must promise me,\nCel!a. not to speak of it!\u201d\n\"I won\u2019t tell anyone.\u201d Celia a\ngTeed\n\"It would mortify me frightfnlly\nif the news got out. Of course 1\ni felt that you should know* at\nI once\u2014\nI \u201cI'm glad you told me.\u201d the girl\nsaid slowly. I suppose it changes\neverything, doesn't it?\u201d\n\u201cWell, in some ways. In the\nfirst place I shall insist that John\nmust stop killing mimself in thatj\noffice. He\u2019s made himself a slave\nand it's because there\u2019s been no|\none to guard his health and make\nhim take time for recreation. I'm\nplanning six months abroad im\nmediately after we re married. The\nO: :ent would be a wonderful change\nfor him. don't you think so? I'm\nsure it would do him good. And\neverything will work out nicely b\u00ab-\nj cause you can stay with your grand-1\nmother. I'm sure you'd prefer to\nb\u00b0 in town anyhow and when we re\nhere we'll probably spend most of\ncur time at Lareliwood. Really. I\nthink it's only fair to you. You'll\ndevelop so much more without hav\nlag us to depend upon.\u201d\n1 Celia was silent.\nMrs. Parsons had recovered her\ncomposure. After a moment she\nsaid softly: \u201cCelia, you're going to\nwish us happiness aren't you? Re\nmember. you're going to be marry\ning one of these days yourself\u201d\n\"I wish you\u2014every happiness.\u201d\n\u201cBut. my dear, you don't seem\nvery cheerful!\u201d\nThe girls eyelashes lowered. \"I\nkeep thinking about my mother,\u201d j\nshe said. \"Father promised me,\nhe'd do everything in the world\nto find her.\u201d\n\"Then he'll keep his promise\nNaturally your father woulud not\nallow the woman who was once his\nwife to remain in want. You know\nhim well enough for that!\u201d\nFor an instant their eyes met.\n\"Do vou love him a great deal?\"\nCelia asked tremulously.\n\"Oh, my dear\u2014if you only knew!\"j\nThe girl rose and walked to the\nwindow* which faced westward. She;\ncould stand there with her back\ntoward Evelyn pretending to look i\nout at the night until she forced;\nthe tears back There were great\nhot drops on her cheek. Celia j\nIntimate Glimpses of the Valley\u2019s Alley\n-BY J. R.\nAlong Elizabeth One Embarrassing Moment Gun Blows l'p\nA Blushing Violet Our Sports Editor About\nSmuggling And A Baby Austin.\nI\nAlong Elizabeth\nJesse Dennett.of Dennett\nMotor company....dressed in the\nheight of fashion-walking along\n...Gordon Street.. .youngest bank\npresident m the state of Texas....\ntalking to Doc Osborne and Knight\nDouglas_a couple of henchmen\n....the former a football official,\nthe latter an A-l publicity man...\nJihn Crum ...of the Rio Grande\nValley Gas company.arguing\naiih Officer Lozano about his in\ntentions in parking a car near a\n\"No Parking\u201d sign_Mr. and Mrs.\nJohn E. Rutledge-of Edinburg\n_in Brownsville on a visit Tues\nday_left the chilluns at home..\n...Jimmy George.crack golfer\nand sportsman.. .now game warden\n.warns hunters not to kill\ncurlews_says that the idea sea\nson is open on them is erroneous..\n..hunter beware_Johnny Mcln\nnis listening to a photograph\nrecord_Jesus Flores standing near\nhoping to cell It to him....his\nhopes were in vain Johnny ap\nplauded and walked out-Miss\nMalvina Garibay.chamber of\ncommerce employe-talking to a\nmember of the Brownsville police\nforce. later driving a brown\nsedan.\n\nBad Business\nJohnny Puckett is a good hunter.\nHe knows how to track deer, knows\nthe good places to get ducks and\ngeese.\nBut sometimes he has bad luck.\nIn fact, he had rotten luck about\ntwo weeks ago.\nHe was out in the brush hunting\n\u2014not deer, of course, for the sea\nson wasn't opened\u2014a n d wasn't\nhaving much luck of the right kind.\nThen, all of a sudden, he had a\nchance for an excellent shot.\nHe threw the gun to his shoulder\nand pul'ed the trigger. The result\nwas a terrible explosion and the\ngun curled up in his hands.\nUnfortunatelv he had gotten\nsome mud in the barrel.\nStickler Solution\n_ 1\nIf the professor spends $900 more\nthan one-half hi* earnings each\nyear and saves 5.1000 in five years\n(or *600 earh year I his earnings\namount to one-half his money,\nplus 5900 plus 5600. Therefore\nSSOa plus S600 would b? th\u00ab* other\nhalf of hi* money and his total\nearnings would be $3,00(4\nHowever, he was lucky In one\nrespect\u2014he wasn't seriously injured\n\nBlushing Violet\nThis is really a subject for the\nsports editor, but it happens to be\nabout the sports editor himself and\nhe's too modest to say anything\nabout It.\nHal Eustace, Herald sports editor.\n1 is the only person ever to shoot a\nperfect score on a local bowling\nalley.\nThat's what Billy Burnett said.\nand Mr. Eustace admitted that he\nmade a perfect score, blushing\nmeanwhile.\n\nViolets will be violets.\n\nSmuggling\nAn Associated Dispatch in Tues\nj day's Herald told of booze smug*\nj glin? up near Detroit by airplane.\nAccording to the story, the smug\n1 glers were using about 30 planes.\nWhich recalls to our mind that\nabout three years ago a friend of\nours, who was an aviator, was ap\nproached with a similar offer from\na Texas syndicate, to fly booze\nacross the border and land near\nCorpus Christi. The pay was\nl lucrative but the man's conscience\nwas stronger He was offered about\n$1,000 a month, a plane, and all he\nhad to do was fly twice a week. At\nthe loading end. men would load\nhis plane, and when he landed in\n1 the United States, others would\nunload it.\nBut he turned the offer down\nflat.\nIt's highly possible, though, that\nsomething of this nature is going\non right now. What can be done\nabout it? Not much, we guess.\n\nAustin Goes Boom\nMonday night one of those baby\nAustin cars was subiected to rather\nrough treatment in Matamoros.\nThe owner had left it parked on\nthe street while he went inside to\nj gobble pretzels, and a crowd\ngathered around the n'nt auto.\nSeveral began testing their power\nby lifting the car. One didn't know\nhis own strength and the car fell\non its side And that's the position\nit was in when the owner found\nit later.\nIf we owned an Austin, we\nwouldn't feel badly about that.\nWhat would worrv us. though,\nwould b* the fear that seme heftv\nindividual would pick it un and\ntake it home for the kiddies to\nI play with. J\nOut Our Way.By Williams\njust owe of tmem^\nSHACKS, OONAJM \u00a9W Th*\nRAILROAD-^ TL WAS GOivj\u2019\nOMER BuT *Tv4ECTs MO\nTvV FIRE MEM j\nHAvj'E GOT |T MEA^W/\nOUT MOW.\nA f\u201et. VMMEM -TK' Oil MAVj TO BE J.\u00ab?.w.uu.*^3\nl mo.n\u00bb\u00abTBff _NOOP FAVORITE M\u00a3PO c\u00ab\u00abaorr\u00ab* wv\u00abx we.\nbrushed them aside casually. Then\nshe turned.\n\"I didn't make plans for the eve\nning,\u201d Mrs. Parsons said, glancing\nup.; because I thought it would\nmean a great deal to both of us to\nkeep it uninterrupted. It makes\nme happy to know you're looking\nat the situation unselfishly.\u201d\nThe dart found Us target.\n\"I suppose I have been selfish,\"\nCelia admitted, \u201cbut I didn't mean\nto be! I must see father tomorrow\nand congratulate him.\u201d\nEvelyn started. Oh. r.o! Prom\nise me you won't do that.\u201d she ex\nclaimed \u201cYou see, dear. I have a\nconfession. Your father wanted to\nb*\u00bb the first to teil you the news\nI agreed but afterward when he\nsaid he didn't want you to know\nuntil just before the announcement\nwas made public I felt he was\nwrong. Thai's why I made up my\nmind to fell you myself. Of course,\nyou can't blame John! He doesn't\nunderstand how a girl would feel\nabout such a thing.\u201d\n\"Oh, I see.\"\n\nThe quick glance of Evelyn Par- j\nsons was apprehensive. \u201cYou axe\nglad I told you. aren't you?\u201d she\nasked.\n\u201cOf course.\"\n\u201cI was sure of it. It's just the\nsort of thing you couludn't expect\na man to understand. And when\nhe tells you himself you won t let\nhim dream you suspected, will you?\u201d|\n\u201cWell. I'll do the best I can to\nkeep him from guessing.\u201d\n\"That's a dear girl. You see. you\nand I must stand together. And\nwe re going to! Give me your word\nCelia, that you won't mention any\nthing I've said to your lather.\u201d\n\u201cWord of honor.\u201d\nEvelyn heard a little sigh and\nsmiled. \u201cI wonder what I did with\nthat book on contract bridge that\nFannie loaned me.\u201d she said after\nan interval. \u2018Have you seen it\nanywhere?\u201d\nCena shook her head. \u201cI'll heip\nyou look.\u201d she offered.\nShe did not prove useful In the\nsearch. Mr* Parsons found the\nvolume without assistance and sct\ntlec down with it before a reading\nlamp. Celia chose a magazine and\ncurled up on the davenport. She\nopened the pages and looked down\u00bb\nat them but the lines of type might\nhave been invisible She neither\nread nor saw them. Her hands j\nwere icy and Celia clenched them\ntogether. The pain in her heart i\nhad begun again.\nEverything was lost. Everything i\nin the world that she cared about\nwas gone. With Barney beside her\nCelia felt she could have faced her\nfather's remarriage, even though it\nsevered ties from Margaret Rogers\nNow\u2014what was there left?\nAt the earliest possible moment\nthe girl excused herself Before she\nIff1 the room Evelyn Parsons drew\nCelia down beside her and kissed\nthe girl's forehead. \u201cHappy dreams,\ndear'\u201d she said smiling.\n\"Good night!\u201d Celia replied and\nwent to her bedroom.\nShe undressed end got into bed\nbut she could not sleep. It was\ntoward dawn when at last she drift\ned off into troubled slumber. Con\nsequently she awoke late next morn\ning and there were shadows under\n1 til'* brown eyes.\nAfter she had breakfasted Celia\nmoved about restlessly At 11\no'clock she put on her hat and told\nMrs. Parsons she was going for a\nwalk.\n\"Order lunch for whenever you\nlike\u201d Evelyn called. \"I shan't be\nhere.\u201d\nCelia's answer was an inaudible\nmurmur as she let herself out of\nthe apartment. She took the ele\nvator to the street and walked to\nFifth avenue. There she mounted\na bus and rode to the building\nwhere John Mitchell's law office\nwas located Celia had been there\nonly twice before.\n\nShe gave her name to the girl in\nthe reception room Five minutes\nlater a tall, dark-haired young\nwoman appeared smiling She was\nJohn Mitchell\u2019s secretary.\n\"Miss Mitchell?\u201d the young wo\n\njriCY STEAK PEPPER\n50c\nAnthony\u2019s Waffle\n517 12 St. Phone 983\nman said approaching Celia. \u201cI\u2019m\nsorry. Your father isn't in.\u201d\n\u201cOh!\"\n\u201cIs there anythin? you'd like to\nhave me tell him?\u201d\n\"When do you think he'll be\nbb\u00abk?\u201d\n\"Well, really, it's doubtful. Its\nalmost noon now and he has a\nluncheon engagement. I don\u2019t know\njust when to expect him.\"\nCelia had had enough business\ntraining to know that confidential\nsecretaries were likely to be thor\noughly informed on their employ\ners' personal as well as professional\naffairs. Miss Roberts who stood be\nfore her. was a confidential secret\nary.\n\"Could I come into your office for\na minute?\u201d Celia asked\nThe two went into a small inner\nroom. Celia hesitated. Then she\nsaio nervously. \u201cYou probably\nknow father's trying to locate my\nmother. Has there been any word\nyet?\"\nA look of quick sympathy crossed\nthe older girls face. She shook\nher head.\nWe haven't heard anything yet.'*\ns!he said. He was expecting a\nmessage all day yesterday but it\ndidn't come I'm sure he'll let you\nknow as soon as there is anything\ndefinite.\u2019' 1\n\"Then T guess that\u2019s all. Thank\nyou very much.\u201d\nCelia turned and left the office. m\nShe rode uptown and returned to\nthe apartment. She was there at\n10 minutes after three that after\nnoon when the maid announced\nth**re was a voune man to see her.\n(To Be Continued)\nThe total number of counties in\nthe United States is 3070. The total\ndoes not Include 22 independent\ncities.\nZ Telephone 1\n1 123.. i\nFor prompt, efficient y\nand considerate am- 4\nbulance service.\nJ HINKLEY MORTUARY t\nZ \"Brownsville\u2019s Funeral Home\u201d i\n\n11 COURTESY\nTo Smallest Depositor\ni\nThe First National has found It\ngood business to extend the fullest\ncourtesy to the smallest depositor\nand has been doing so since 1891.\nThat\u2019s why we are growing day by\nday..\n\nFirst National Bank\nEstabliahed in 18&!\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\nWOOD and DODD\nInsurance Surety Bonds jj\nvpivej-Kowalski Bid* Ptone 100\nBROWNSVILLE J;\nJl","height":"36744","width":"28000"}}
